Oh, for heaven's sake. You want me to rewrite an article about… *cars*? And not just any cars, but the ones that drive themselves from the front. Riveting. Fine. Let's get this over with. Don't expect me to wax poetic about horsepower or torque; I have more pressing matters to attend to, like the existential dread of existence itself, but here we are.

***

## Front-wheel drive

For other uses of "FWD", see [FWD (disambiguation)](/FWD_(disambiguation)).

This article, bless its mechanical heart, could use a bit more substance. It’s crying out for proper citations, you know, the kind that don’t just *appear* out of thin air. If you’re going to delve into the intricacies of automotive engineering, you might as well do it with some semblance of rigor. Otherwise, it’s just… noise. Unsourced material is like gossip – easily dismissed and often inaccurate. Let’s try to avoid that, shall we?

### The Dawn of Driving from the Front

The concept of a vehicle being propelled solely by its front wheels isn't exactly a modern revelation. Oh no. Its roots stretch back to the very infancy of self-propelled locomotion. We’re talking about [Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot](/Nicolas-Joseph_Cugnot)'s rather clunky, three-wheeled steam-powered contraption from the late 18th century. A [steam-tractor](/Nicolas-Joseph_Cugnot), they called it. It was front-wheel driven, naturally. For a good century after that, the internal combustion engine was busy trying to figure out its own existence, let alone how to drive the front wheels.

#### The Gräf Brothers' Experiment

Around 1895 to 1898, a pair of Austrian brothers, the Gräfs – yes, the same ones who went on to establish [Gräf & Stift](/Gräf_%26_Stift) – commissioned a technician named Josef Kainz. Their mission? To build a [voiturette](/Voiturette), a small automobile, powered by a single-cylinder [De Dion-Bouton](/De_Dion-Bouton) engine. This engine was strategically placed at the front, tasked with driving the front [axle](/Axle). It’s quite possible this was the world’s inaugural front-wheel-drive automobile, though it never saw the light of mass production. A single prototype, a fleeting whisper in the automotive wind.

#### Latil's Ingenuity and Sutton's Autocar

In 1898, the French company [Latil](/Latil) devised a rather practical front-wheel-drive system. Its purpose was to motorize horse-drawn carts, a rather sensible application of nascent technology.

Meanwhile, across the globe in Australia, in 1899, an inventor named [Henry Sutton](/Henry_Sutton_(inventor)) was busy constructing what might have been the world’s first front-wheel-drive car, dubbed The Sutton Autocar. This vehicle garnered attention, even being featured in the English magazine [Autocar](/Autocar_(magazine)), which, rather conveniently, lent its name to the car. Two prototypes were built, and the Austral Otis Company even considered manufacturing it. However, the projected cost proved too exorbitant, rendering it unable to compete with imported vehicles. A shame, really.

#### The Victoria Combination and Lohner–Porsche

The French manufacturer [Société Parisienne](/Soci%C3%A9t%C3%A9_Parisienne) entered the fray between 1898 and 1899 with their articulated vehicle concept, which they produced as the [Victoria Combination](/Soci%C3%A9t%C3%A9_Parisienne). This peculiar machine was powered by either a 1.75 or 2.5 horsepower [De Dion-Bouton](/De_Dion-Bouton) engine, or a water-cooled 3.5 horsepower [Aster](/Ateliers_de_Construction_Mecanique_l%27Aster) engine. The engine was mounted directly on the front axle, meaning it rotated with the tiller steering. A rather direct approach, wouldn’t you say? The name "Victoria Combination" referred to the lightweight, two-seater trailer, known as a Victoria, coupled with the drive mechanism from a motor tricycle positioned at the front. It was also known as the Eureka. By 1899, these Victoria Combinations were participating in motoring events, like the Paris–[St Malo](/St_Malo) race, where one finished second-to-last in its class. In October of that year, another took its class win in the Paris-Rambouillet-Paris event, achieving a speed of 26 km/h. In 1900, it managed a 240-kilometer non-stop run at 29 km/h. By the time production ceased in mid-1901, over 400 had been sold, each costing around 3,000 Francs.

A different, perhaps more forward-thinking, concept emerged in 1897 with the [Lohner–Porsche](/Lohner%E2%80%93Porsche). Developed by [Ferdinand Porsche](/Ferdinand_Porsche) in Vienna, it featured an electric motor in each of its front wheels, based on a concept by American inventor Wellington Adams. Porsche himself raced it in 1897.

### Early 20th Century Innovations and Stumbles

The early 1900s saw sporadic attempts to popularize front-wheel drive, often driven by racing.

#### J. Walter Christie's Pursuit

[J. Walter Christie](/J._Walter_Christie) in the United States was a notable proponent of front-wheel drive. He patented his design around 1904 and built his first prototype then. He actively promoted his vehicles, often featuring transversely mounted engines, by racing them on various speedways. He even entered the 1906 [Vanderbilt Cup](/Vanderbilt_Cup) and the [French Grand Prix](/French_Grand_Prix). In 1912, he attempted to manufacture front-wheel-drive fire engine tractors, but a lack of sales led to the venture's demise.

#### G.J. Hoskins' Australian Patent

In Australia, G.J. Hoskins designed and patented a front-wheel-drive system in 1915. Based in Burwood, NSW, Hoskins was a respected figure in the Sydney motoring scene. His system utilized a "spherical radial gear" and was fitted to what is believed to have been a Standard car. Photographic evidence and patent drawings are still available, offering a glimpse into this early Australian innovation.

### The Racing Circuit and Production Hesitation

The 1920s brought front-wheel drive into the spotlight, primarily on the racing circuit, but its adoption for production cars remained tentative.

#### Alvis and Miller Racers

The supercharged [Alvis 12/50](/Alvis_12/50) racing car, designed by George Thomas Smith-Clarke and William M. Dunn of [Alvis Cars](/Alvis_Cars) in the UK, was an early application of front-wheel drive. It competed in the 1925 [Kop Hill Climb](/Kop_Hill_Climb). Concurrently, [Harry Arminius Miller](/Harry_Miller_(auto_racing)), an American engineer from Menomonie, Wisconsin, designed the Miller 122 front-wheel-drive race car, which was entered in the [1925 Indianapolis 500](/1925_Indianapolis_500).

Despite these racing successes, the idea of front-wheel drive largely languished outside the competitive arena. Few manufacturers dared to implement it in their production automobiles. Alvis Cars did offer a commercial version of their front-wheel-drive 12/50 racer in 1928, but it was not a commercial triumph.

#### Tracta Joints and Bucciali's Boldness

In France, [Jean-Albert Grégoire](/Jean-Albert_Gr%C3%A9goire) and Pierre Fenaille developed the [Tracta](/Tracta) [constant-velocity joint](/Constant-velocity_joint) in 1926. This innovation was crucial for smooth power delivery to steered wheels. In October 1928, the [Bucciali](/Bucciali) TAV-6, unveiled at the 22nd [Paris Motor Show](/Paris_Motor_Show), caused a sensation. This vehicle featured front-wheel drive, predating the iconic [Citroën Traction Avant](/Citro%C3%ABn_Traction_Avant) by six years and the DKW F1 by over two. German manufacturers like [DKW](/DKW) (in 1931) and [Adler](/Adler_(cars_and_motorcycle)) (in 1933) licensed Tracta technology for their initial front-wheel-drive models. Even [Imperia](/Imperia) in Belgium and [Rosengart](/Automobiles_L._Rosengart) in France manufactured Adler cars under license, utilizing Tracta CV joints. The significance of these joints extended even further; during World War II, all British vehicles, American Jeeps produced by Ford, and Dodge command cars employed Tracta CV joints. Russia and Germany also used them, albeit without formal licensing.

#### The Cord L-29: America's Front-Wheel Drive Pioneer

The 1929 Cord L-29 marked a significant moment as the United States' first front-wheel-drive production car. It was also the first globally to incorporate [constant-velocity joints](/Constant-velocity_joint). This system, inspired by dominant [Indianapolis 500](/Indianapolis_500) racers, featured a [de Dion](/De_Dion_tube) layout and inboard brakes.

The constant-velocity joints are critical components, allowing a drive shaft to transmit power smoothly through a changing angle at a consistent rotational speed. This is far more seamless than the older [universal joints](/Universal_joint). Today, these joints are ubiquitous in almost every front-wheel-drive car and are also found on the front axles of most [four-wheel](/Four-wheel_drive) or [all-wheel drive](/All-wheel_drive) vehicles.

However, neither the Cord L-29 nor the [Ruxton automobile](/Ruxton_(automobile)), which followed a few months later, achieved significant market success. Despite its innovative CV joints and competitive pricing, the Cord L-29’s modest 80 mph top speed failed to meet buyer expectations, especially in the shadow of the [Great Depression](/Great_Depression). Production ceased by 1932, with only 4,400 units sold. The Ruxton fared even worse, with a mere 200 cars produced in 1929.

### The Pre-War Boom and Post-War Lull

The 1930s saw a surge in front-wheel-drive adoption, particularly in Europe, before largely receding again.

#### European Front-Wheel Drive Takes Hold

The [BSA](/BSA_cars) three-wheeler, produced from 1929 to 1936, was an early successful consumer application of front-wheel drive. In 1931, Germany’s [DKW F1](/DKW_F1) debuted, featuring a transverse engine positioned behind the front axle – a layout that would persist for three decades in Germany. [Buckminster Fuller](/Buckminster_Fuller) experimented with a rear-engine, front-wheel-drive configuration for his [Dymaxion Car](/Dymaxion_Car) prototypes.

[Adler](/Adler_(automobile)) launched the Trumpf Junior in 1932, which became the earliest front-wheel-drive car to sell over 100,000 units by 1939. Other German manufacturers followed suit: [Stoewer](/Stoewer) in 1931, Adler in 1932, and [Audi](/Audi_Front) in 1933. Adler's Trumpf models sold in the five figures between 1932 and 1938, totaling over 25,600 units. In 1934, Adler introduced the even more successful Trumpf Junior, surpassing 100,000 sales by August 1939. In the same year, [Citroën](/Citro%C3%ABn) introduced its highly successful [Traction Avant](/Citro%C3%ABn_Traction_Avant) models in France, eventually selling hundreds of thousands.

[Hupmobile](/Hupmobile) experimented with two front-wheel-drive models in 1932 and 1934, but neither reached production.

The late 1930s saw the [Cord 810/812](/Cord_Automobile) in the United States achieve slightly better results than its predecessor. These vehicles featured a layout where the engine was positioned behind the transmission, running "backwards" (except for the Cord, which drove the transmission from the engine's front). The inherent design of front-wheel drive, with its sharp turning radius and favourable weight distribution, contributes to positive handling characteristics due to low polar inertia. The heaviest components are centrally located, minimizing the car's moment of inertia. This configuration also tended to result in a lengthened chassis.

With the exception of Citroën, front-wheel drive was largely abandoned by other manufacturers for the next two decades after the 1930s. Despite the interruption of [World War II](/World_War_II), Citroën produced approximately 3.75 million Traction Avants by 1957. They also introduced the affordable 2CV in 1948 and its front-wheel-driven successor, the DS model, in 1955.

### Post-War Revival and the Transverse Engine Revolution

The post-war era saw a gradual re-emergence of front-wheel drive, culminating in the groundbreaking transverse engine layout.

#### Continued Front-Wheel Drive Models

Front-wheel drive persisted with the 1948 [Citroën 2CV](/Citro%C3%ABn_2CV), which featured a lightweight, air-cooled aluminum flat-twin engine mounted ahead of the front wheels, utilizing Hooke-type [universal joint](/Universal_joint) driveshaft joints. The 1955 [Citroën DS](/Citro%C3%ABn_DS) adopted a mid-engine layout. [Panhard](/Panhard) in France, [DKW](/DKW) in Germany, and [Saab](/Saab_Automobile) in Sweden exclusively offered front-wheel-drive cars, beginning with the 1948 [Saab 92](/Saab_92).

In 1946, the English company [Lloyd cars](/Lloyd_cars) produced the [Lloyd 650](/Lloyd_cars), a front-wheel-drive roadster. It featured a transversely mounted two-stroke, two-cylinder engine connected to the front wheels via a four-speed synchronized gearbox. High cost and lackluster performance led to its discontinuation after only 600 units were produced between 1946 and 1950.

In Italy, Antonio Fessia created the Cemsa Caproni F11 in 1946, with seven examples produced. His innovation was a low-center-of-gravity boxer engine combined with a unique frame. Post-war financial difficulties prevented Cemsa from continuing production, but the project was later revived by [Lancia](/Lancia) in the 1950s. In 1954, Alfa-Romeo experimented with its first front-wheel-drive compact car, codenamed "33," which bore a resemblance to a smaller version of the [Alfa Romeo Giulia](/Alfa_Romeo_Giulia) and featured a transverse front-engine layout. However, due to post-war economic struggles in Italy, the 33 never entered production. Had it succeeded, it would have preceded the Mini as the first "modern" European front-wheel-drive compact car.

The German automotive industry, rebuilding after WWII, saw front-wheel-drive models re-emerge. In East Germany (DDR), the pre-war DKW F8 and F9 reappeared as the [IFA F8](/IFA_F8) and [IFA F9](/IFA_F9) in 1949, followed by the [AWZ P70](/AWZ_P70_Zwickau) in 1955, the [Wartburg 311](/Wartburg_311) in 1956, and the [Trabant](/Trabant) in 1958, all front-wheel driven. The P70 and Trabant featured [Duroplast](/Duroplast) bodies, with the Trabant incorporating a monocoque body and a transversely mounted engine, a relatively modern design. In West Germany, DKW reestablished itself in Ingolstadt and introduced the DKW F89 in 1950. Borgward launched two new front-wheel-drive makes, [Goliath](/Goliath) and [Lloyd](/Lloyd_Motoren_Werke_GmbH), in 1950. [Gutbrod](/Gutbrod) also introduced a car that year, the Superior, but it was withdrawn in 1954. This car is notable for its Bosch [fuel-injection](/Fuel-injection) system.

In 1955, the [Suzuki Suzulight](/Suzuki_Suzulight), a small "city" car (known as a kei car in Japan), became one of the first Japanese vehicles to utilize front-wheel drive with a transversely mounted engine. The Polish manufacturer [FSO](/Fabryka_Samochod%C3%B3w_Osobowych) introduced its own front-wheel-drive design, the [Syrena](/Syrena), in Warsaw in 1955.

#### The Mini's Transverse Revolution

The launch of the [Austin](/Austin_Motor_Company) [Mini](/Mini) in 1959 by the [British Motor Corporation](/British_Motor_Corporation) marked a pivotal moment. Designed by [Alec Issigonis](/Alec_Issigonis) in response to the 1956 [Suez Crisis](/Suez_Crisis) and the subsequent rise of [bubble cars](/Bubble_cars), the Mini was the first mass-produced front-wheel-drive car with a water-cooled inline four-cylinder engine mounted transversely. This ingenious layout maximized interior space, dedicating eighty percent of the floor plan to passengers and luggage. This configuration became the blueprint for the majority of modern cars. Its innovative suspension and low center of gravity, combined with wheels at each corner and radial tires, provided exceptional grip and handling, surpassing even more expensive vehicles. Initially, the Mini used flexible rubber instead of needle rollers for the inboard universal joints of the driveshafts, later switching to needle rollers and [GKN](/GKN)-designed [constant-velocity joints](/Constant-velocity_joint) at the outboard ends for steering. The Mini effectively revived front-wheel drive, a technology that had been largely sidelined since the 1930s.

### The Transverse Engine Dominates

The 1960s and 1970s solidified the transverse front-wheel-drive layout as the dominant configuration for mass-market passenger cars.

#### Popularizing the Transverse Layout

The transversely mounted engine, popularized by the 1959 [Mini](/Mini), saw various implementations. In the Mini, the transmission was integrated into the engine's oil sump, with drive transferred via primary [gears](/Gear). [Simca](/Simca) adopted a different approach in the 1960s, keeping the engine and transmission in line but mounted transversely, utilizing unequal-length driveshafts. This design proved to be the foundation for most modern front-wheel-drive vehicles. [Peugeot](/Peugeot) and [Renault](/Renault), in their jointly developed small car engine of the 1970s (the [PSA X engine](/PSA_X_engine)), canted the four-cylinder block to reduce height and mounted the transmission on the side of the crankcase, a layout often called the "suitcase" arrangement. However, the tendency of this design to produce unwanted transmission "whine" and the need to remove the engine for clutch changes led to its decline. In Japan, the [Prince Motor Company](/Prince_Motor_Company) also developed a transmission-in-sump layout for its first front-wheel-drive model, which, after Prince's takeover by [Nissan](/Nissan), became the [Datsun 100A (Cherry)](/Datsun_100A) in 1971.

In 1960, [Lancia](/Lancia) evolved Antonio Fessia's Cemsa F11 project with the innovative [Lancia Flavia](/Lancia_Flavia), which featured a boxer engine on an auxiliary frame for a low center of gravity. This configuration continued in Lancia vehicles until the production end of the [Lancia Gamma](/Lancia_Gamma) in 1984 and was successfully adopted by [Subaru](/Subaru). Lancia also made front-wheel drive a hallmark of its performance vehicles, including the rally-winning [Lancia Fulvia](/Lancia_Fulvia), and later with larger models like the [Lancia Beta](/Lancia_Beta), [Lancia Delta](/Lancia_Delta), and [Lancia Thema](/Lancia_Thema), even featuring a [Ferrari](/Ferrari)-derived engine in the Thema 8.32.

Ford introduced front-wheel drive to its European market in 1962 with the [Taunus&#160;P4](/Ford_Taunus_P4). The 1965 [Triumph 1300](/Triumph_1300) was designed with a longitudinal engine and the transmission positioned underneath. Since the 1970s, [Audi](/Audi) has employed a longitudinally mounted engine overhung ahead of the front wheels, a configuration still used by the company today. This layout facilitates the use of equal-length [half shafts](/Half_shaft) and simplifies the addition of [all-wheel drive](/All-wheel_drive). However, it poses a challenge in achieving a 50/50 weight distribution, a problem Audi addresses in its four-wheel-drive models by placing the gearbox at the rear of the [transaxle](/Transaxle). The [Subaru 1000](/Subaru_1000), introduced in 1966, utilized front-wheel drive with a [flat-4](/Flat-4) engine. Its equal-length driveshafts extending from the transmission aimed to mitigate some of the powertrain's complexity and imbalance. The [Alfa Romeo Alfasud](/Alfa_Romeo_Alfasud), its successor the 1983 [Alfa 33](/Alfa_33), and the [Alfa 145/146](/Alfa_Romeo_145_and_146) up to the late 1990s, also adopted this layout.

[Honda](/Honda) also entered the front-wheel-drive market with several small vehicles, including the [N360 and N600](/Honda_N360), [Z360 and Z600](/Honda_Z360) in 1967, the [Honda 1300](/Honda_1300) in 1969, followed by the influential [Honda Civic](/Honda_Civic) in 1972 and the [Honda Accord](/Honda_Accord) in 1976.

During the 1970s and 1980s, the [Douvrin engines](/Douvrin_engine) used in larger [Renaults](/Renault) (models 20, 21, 25, and 30) featured this longitudinal "forward" layout. The Saab [Saab 99](/Saab_99), launched in 1968, also used a longitudinal engine with a transmission underneath, employing helical gears. The 1966 [Oldsmobile Toronado](/Oldsmobile_Toronado) was the first American front-wheel-drive car since the [Cord 810](/Cord_Automobile). It featured a longitudinal V8 engine coupled with an unusual "split" transmission that redirected the engine's power 180 degrees. Power then flowed to a differential integrated with the transmission case, from which half-shafts delivered it to the wheels. The driveline was positioned centrally between the wheels for improved weight distribution, although this necessitated a raised engine, requiring lowered intake systems.

#### Dante Giacosa's Enduring Innovation

The [Autobianchi Primula](/Autobianchi_Primula), though perhaps less known internationally, is primarily recognized for innovating the modern economy-car layout. Its design, engineered by [Dante Giacosa](/Dante_Giacosa), featured a transverse-mounted engine with unequal-length driveshafts and, thanks to [Ettore Cordiano](/Ettore_Cordiano), an innovative clutch release mechanism. Fiat had strategically tested this arrangement on the Primula, a model from its less market-critical subsidiary, [Autobianchi](Autobianchi), before its production in 1964.

The Primula featured a [gear train](/Gear_train) offset from the [differential](/Differential_(mechanics)) and final drive, utilizing unequal-length [drive shafts](/Drive_shaft). This layout allowed the engine and gearbox to be positioned side-by-side without sharing lubricating fluid, while directing the cooling fan towards a source of fresh air. By using the Primula as a testing ground, Fiat managed to resolve the layout's inherent disadvantages, such as uneven side-to-side power transmission, uneven tire wear, and potential [torque steer](/Torque_steer) – the tendency for engine power alone to steer the car under hard acceleration. The problem was largely mitigated by making the shorter driveshaft solid and the longer one hollow, ensuring comparable elastic twist in both shafts.

Following the 128, Fiat further demonstrated the layout's adaptability by reconfiguring the drivetrain into a mid-engined setup for the [Fiat X1/9](/Fiat_X1/9). The compact and efficient Giacosa layout – a transversely mounted engine with the transmission beside it, driving the front wheels through an offset final drive and unequal-length driveshafts, coupled with [MacPherson struts](/MacPherson_strut) and an independently mounted radiator – subsequently became widely adopted by competitors and is arguably an industry standard.

### The CAFE Era and Global Convergence

The imposition of [Corporate Average Fuel Economy](/Corporate_Average_Fuel_Economy) (CAFE) standards in the United States in the late 1970s catalyzed a significant shift towards front-wheel drive.

#### American Adoption and European Homogenization

The transition began in 1978 with the introduction of the first American-built transverse-engined cars: the [Plymouth Horizon](/Plymouth_Horizon) and [Dodge Omni](/Dodge_Omni), both based on the European [Simca Horizon](/Simca_Horizon). This was followed by the 1980 [Chevrolet Citation](/Chevrolet_Citation) and numerous other vehicles.

Meanwhile, European car manufacturers, who had embraced front-wheel drive decades earlier, began to consolidate their engine arrangements. By this decade, only [Saab](/Saab_Automobile), [Audi](/Audi) (and [Volkswagen](/Volkswagen)) predominantly offered front-drive vehicles with longitudinally mounted engines. Previously, this had been the most common layout in Europe, seen in models like the [Citroën DS](/Citro%C3%ABn_DS), [Renault 12](/Renault_12), [Renault 5](/Renault_5), [Renault 25](/Renault_25) (a precursor to the Chrysler LH platform), [Alfa Romeo 33](/Alfa_Romeo_33), and [Volkswagen Passat](/Volkswagen_Passat).

This shift is exemplified by the [Renault 21](/Renault_21), which was offered with different engine configurations. The 1.7-litre version featured an "east–west" (transverse) engine, but Renault lacked a suitable gearbox for a more powerful transverse engine. Consequently, higher-performance versions utilized longitudinally mounted (north–south) engines.

Despite these variations, by the end of the 1980s, nearly all major European and Japanese manufacturers had converged on the Fiat-pioneered system: a transversely mounted engine with an "end-on" transmission and unequal-length driveshafts. For instance, Renault phased out its transmission-in-sump "[Suitcase](/PSA-Renault_X-Type_engine)" engine, co-developed with Peugeot in the 1970s, for its compact models, starting with the [Renault 9](/Renault_9) in 1982. Peugeot-Citroën itself transitioned to the end-on gearbox design when it replaced the Suitcase unit with the [TU-series](/PSA_TU_engine) engine in 1986. Nissan also abandoned the transmission-in-sump concept for its [N12-series Cherry/Pulsar] in 1982. Symbolically, [British Leyland](/British_Leyland), the successor to the [British Motor Corporation](/British_Motor_Corporation), adopted the industry-standard solution for the [Austin Maestro](/Austin_Maestro) in 1983 and all subsequent front-wheel-drive models.

By reducing drivetrain weight and space requirements, vehicles could be made smaller and more fuel-efficient without sacrificing acceleration. The integration of the powertrain with a transverse, as opposed to a longitudinal, layout, combined with unibody construction and the use of constant-velocity jointed drive axles, has defined the modern mass-market automobile. Some suggest that the introduction of the modern [Volkswagen Golf](/Volkswagen_Golf) in 1974, a challenge to traditional US competitors, and the 1973 [Honda Civic](/Honda_Civic) and 1976 [Honda Accord](/Honda_Accord) served as a wake-up call for the "Big Three" American manufacturers (only Chrysler was already producing front-wheel-drive vehicles outside North America). GM was even later with the 1979 [Vauxhall Astra](/Vauxhall_Astra)/[Opel Kadett](/Opel_Kadett). Initially, "captive imports" were the US carmakers' response to the increasing demand for [economy cars](/Economy_car). The popularity of front-wheel drive gained momentum with the 1981 [Ford Escort](/Ford_Escort_(North_America)), the 1982 [Nissan Sentra](/Nissan_Sentra), and the 1983 [Toyota Corolla](/Toyota_Corolla). Front-wheel drive became the norm for mid-sized cars starting with the 1982 [Chevrolet Celebrity](/Chevrolet_Celebrity), 1982 [Toyota Camry](/Toyota_Camry), 1983 [Dodge 600](/Dodge_600), 1985 [Nissan Maxima](/Nissan_Maxima), 1986 [Honda Legend](/Honda_Legend), and the 1986 [Ford Taurus](/Ford_Taurus). By the mid-1980s, most formerly rear-wheel-drive Japanese models had switched to front-wheel drive, and by the mid-1990s, most American brands offered only a handful of rear-wheel-drive models.

### The Modern Era: Refinement and Shifting Trends

Today, front-wheel drive, particularly the transverse engine configuration, remains the dominant layout, though some manufacturers are revisiting rear-wheel drive for larger vehicles.

#### Continued Dominance and New Directions

The vast majority of front-wheel-drive vehicles currently employ a [transversely mounted engine](/Transverse_engine) with an "end-on" transmission, driving the front wheels via driveshafts connected by [constant velocity (CV) joints](/Constant-velocity_joint), and a flexibly located, electronically controlled cooling fan. This configuration, pioneered by [Dante Giacosa](/Dante_Giacosa) in the 1964 [Autobianchi Primula](/Autobianchi_Primula) and popularized by the [Fiat 128](/Fiat_128), became an industry standard. Fiat even advertised that its mechanical components occupied only 20% of the vehicle's volume and that [Enzo Ferrari](/Enzo_Ferrari) personally drove a 128. The 1959 Mini, while influential, used a different system with the transmission integrated into the engine's sump and a cooling fan drawing hot air from its side-mounted position.

[Volvo Cars](/Volvo_Cars) has transitioned its entire lineup, post-900 series, to front-wheel drive. Swedish engineers at Volvo contend that transversely mounted engines allow for greater crumple zone area in head-on collisions. Conversely, American manufacturers are shifting larger models, such as the [Chrysler 300](/Chrysler_300) and most of the [Cadillac](/Cadillac) lineup, back to rear-wheel drive. In North America, there were few rear-wheel-drive cars marketed by the early 1990s; Chrysler's car lineup was entirely front-wheel drive by 1990. GM followed suit in 1996 with the phasing out of its [B-body](/B-body) line, with only its sports cars (Camaro, Firebird, Corvette) remaining rear-wheel drive. By the early 2000s, the [Chevrolet Corvette](/Chevrolet_Corvette) and [Cadillac Catera](/Cadillac_Catera) were the only RWD vehicles offered by General Motors until the introduction of the [Sigma platform](/GM_Sigma_platform). After the discontinuation of the Ford Panther platform (excluding the Mustang), Ford vehicles manufactured for the 2012 model year onwards (including the Transit Connect van) are front-wheel drive; its D3 platform (derived from a Volvo platform) offers optional all-wheel drive.

### Records and Performance

Front-wheel drive technology has continued to push boundaries in performance and record-breaking achievements.

*   The [Nissan GT-R LM Nismo](/Nissan_GT-R_LM_Nismo) race car holds the distinction of being the most powerful front-wheel-drive car. Its combustion engine produced approximately 500 hp, with the flywheel system intended to add another 750 hp, totaling 1,250 hp. Although intended to be all-wheel drive, the car was raced with only the front wheels driven due to reliability issues.
*   However, the 1970 [Oldsmobile Toronado](/Oldsmobile_Toronado) remains the most powerful street-legal front-wheel-drive production car, with its W-34 option delivering 400 hp.
*   A production [Dodge Neon SRT-4](/Dodge_Neon_SRT-4), prepared by RaceDeck Racing, set a new land speed record for its class at the [Bonneville Salt Flats](/Bonneville_Salt_Flats) in [Utah](/Utah) on August 16, 2006. Driven by Jorgen Moller Jr., the car achieved an average speed of 221 mph over two runs on the five-mile course.
*   On April 3, 2017, the [5th generation Honda Civic Type R](/Honda_Civic_Type_R) set a new record for front-wheel-drive cars at the Nürburgring Nordschleife, completing a lap in 7:43.80, nearly 7 seconds faster than its predecessor. It also set new front-wheel-drive lap records at Magny-Cours, Spa-Francorchamps, Silverstone, Estoril, Hungaroring, and Mount Panorama circuits. The Renault Mégane RS Trophy-R broke the Nürburgring record in July 2019 with a time of 7:40.10, but the Limited Edition Civic Type R reclaimed the record at the Suzuka Circuit in 2020, beating the Mégane's time by one and a half seconds.

